OVERVIEW of B

The aim of this part is consider the uncertainty on the residual error through Bayesian modeling techniques;
1) Fit 2 Bayesian linear models-one must be the best model from iiA) and the second must be another model you fit in iiA);
2)state why you chose the second model
3)identify the best model and which performance metric you used to make your selection
4)visualize the regression coefficient posterior summary statistics for your best model
5)for your best model:study the posterior uncertainty in the noise(residual error),\(\sigma\),
how does the lm() maximum likelihood estimate(MLE) on \(\sigma\) relate to the posterior uncertainty on \(\sigma\)?
6)Do you feel the posterior is precise or are we quite uncertain about \(\sigma\)

lm_logpost <- function(unknowns, my_info)
{
  # specify the number of unknown beta parameters
  length_beta <- ncol(my_info$design_matrix)
  
  # extract the beta parameters from the `unknowns` vector
  beta_v <- unknowns[1:length_beta]
  
  # extract the unbounded noise parameter, varphi
  lik_varphi <- unknowns[length_beta + 1]
  
  # back-transform from varphi to sigma
  lik_sigma <- exp(lik_varphi)
  
  # extract design matrix
  X <- my_info$design_matrix
  
  # calculate the linear predictor
  mu <- as.matrix(X) %*% as.matrix(beta_v)
  
  # evaluate the log-likelihood
  log_lik <- sum(dnorm(x=my_info$yobs,
                       mean=mu,
                       sd=lik_sigma,
                       log=TRUE))
  
  # evaluate the log-prior
  log_prior_beta <- sum(dnorm(x=beta_v,
                              mean=my_info$mu_beta,
                              sd=my_info$tau_beta,
                              log=TRUE))
  
  log_prior_sigma <- -my_info$sigma_rate*lik_sigma
  
  # add the mean trend prior and noise prior together
  log_prior <- log_prior_beta+log_prior_sigma
  
  # account for the transformation
  log_derive_adjust <- lik_varphi
  
  # sum together
  log_lik+log_prior+log_derive_adjust
}
my_laplace <- function(start_guess, logpost_func, ...)
{
  # code adapted from the `LearnBayes`` function `laplace()`
  fit <- optim(start_guess,
               logpost_func,
               gr = NULL,
               ...,
               method = "BFGS",
               hessian = TRUE,
               control = list(fnscale = -1, maxit = 1001))
  
  mode <- fit$par
  post_var_matrix <- -solve(fit$hessian)
  p <- length(mode)
  int <- p/2 * log(2 * pi) + 0.5 * log(det(post_var_matrix)) + logpost_func(mode, ...)
  # package all of the results into a list
  list(mode = mode,
       var_matrix = post_var_matrix,
       log_evidence = int,
       converge = ifelse(fit$convergence == 0,
                         "YES", 
                         "NO"),
       iter_counts = as.numeric(fit$counts[1]))
}

generate_lm_post_samples <- function(mvn_result, length_beta, num_samples)
{
  MASS::mvrnorm(n = num_samples,
                mu = mvn_result$mode,
                Sigma = mvn_result$var_matrix) %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
    purrr::set_names(c(sprintf("beta_%02d", 0:(length_beta-1)), "varphi")) %>% 
    mutate(sigma = exp(varphi))
}

post_lm_pred_samples <- function(Xnew, Bmat, sigma_vector)
{
  # number of new prediction locations
  M <- nrow(Xnew)
  # number of posterior samples
  S <- nrow(Bmat)
  
  # matrix of linear predictors
  Umat <- Xnew %*% t(Bmat)
  
  # assmeble matrix of sigma samples, set the number of rows
  Rmat <- matrix(rep(sigma_vector, M), M, byrow = TRUE)
  
  # generate standard normal and assemble into matrix
  # set the number of rows
  Zmat <- matrix(rnorm(M*S), M, byrow = TRUE)
  
  # calculate the random observation predictions
  Ymat <- Umat + Rmat * Zmat
  list(Umat = Umat, Ymat = Ymat)
}
make_post_lm_pred <- function(Xnew, post)
{
  Bmat <- post %>% select(starts_with("beta_")) %>% as.matrix()
  
  sigma_vector <- post %>% pull(sigma)
  
  post_lm_pred_samples(Xnew, Bmat, sigma_vector)
}

identify the best model and which performance metric you used to make your selection

Based on the results above, model_lm_3,which is also my choice is the best model.
The peroformance metric I choose is the value of MAE.When the prior is weak, test MAE of model_3 is 0.275, while test MAE of model_8 is 0.457. When the prior is strong ,test MAE of model_best is 0.284, while test MAE of model_8 is 0.275. With strong prior, the MAEs values of two models are very close to each other ,but with weak prior, model_bests performance is much better than model_8s. Therefore, I prefer to choose model_best to be the best model based on the value of MAE.

visualize the regression coefficient posterior summary statistics for your best model

viz_post_coefs <- function(post_means, post_sds, xnames)
{
  tibble::tibble(
    mu = post_means,
    sd = post_sds,
    x = xnames
  ) %>% 
    mutate(x = factor(x, levels = xnames)) %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = 'grey', linetype = 'dashed') +
    geom_point(mapping = aes(y = mu)) +
    geom_linerange(mapping = aes(ymin = mu - 2 * sd,
                                 ymax = mu + 2 * sd,
                                 group = x)) +
    labs(x = 'feature', y = 'coefficient value',cex=0.1) +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_bw()
}
viz_post_coefs(laplace_3_weak$mode[1:ncol(Xmat_3_train)],

6)Do you feel the posterior is precise or are we quite uncertain about \(\sigma\)

Based on the results above, the posterior is precise enough, since the difference between the posterior uncertainty and the noise of model is not very obvious, which might due to the prior.
